Addendum: J-Stream Tensor Autocorrelation as
Third-Order Stylometric
Appended to: “A Universal Structural-Procedural Index: Emergent Identity, Meter and
Rhythm in Music and Literature — Strange Loops in Bijective Braidings”
Third-Order Stylometric: Tensor Autocorrelation
The J-stream sign-flip rate (first tested as a candidate stylometric) proved uninformative —
all works cluster near 0.5, the channel operating at entropy saturation. The tensor
autocorrelation at lags 1-12 reveals what the scalar measure cannot: the periodic structure
embedded in the ternary event sequence.
For each corpus, the autocorrelation of the full J stream and the nonzero-only J stream was
computed at lags 1 through 12. The dominant period and its strength are reported.
Results:
The music/text boundary is unambiguous. Musical works produce periodic
autocorrelation profiles with strength 0.07-0.12. Literary works produce near-noise profiles
at 0.02-0.04. The tensor discriminates music from text at a level the J-stream distribution
alone cannot.
The Sarabande. The slowest movement produces the strongest periodic signal — lag 7,
strength 0.1202. Consistent with its triple metre and dotted rhythm. The Sarabande’s
